Multicollinearity¶

In [27]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
variables = cleaned_data[['TotalSteps','TotalDistance','Total_Active_Minutes']]
vif = pd.DataFrame()
vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(variables.values, i) for i in range(variables.shape[1])]
vif["Features"] = variables.columns
vif
Out[27]:
VIF Features
0 106.257688 TotalSteps
1 98.932423 TotalDistance
2 3.037008 Total_Active_Minutes

Variance inflation factor is higher than 10, indicating a multicollinearity problem. Multiple linear regression model might not be appropriate to this study.

Main findings:¶

  1. Most of users (29/33) frequently (more than 80%) used fitness device to record their activities during a month.
  2. 26/33 users recorded more than 1000 minutes activity per day (1440 minutes in a day)
  3. Averaged daily steps for most users (26/33) were less than recommended 10000 daily step for general fitness.
  4. Averaged daily distance for 31/33 users were less than recommended 8 kilometers
  5. The most daily activity minutes were recorded on Monday and Tuesday, while the most daily activity distance were recorded on Saturday and Tuesday.
  6. Very active minutes and total steps have the most significant effect on calories. On the other hand, sedentary minutes is negatively correlated with calories.

Recommendation (based on limited dataset):¶

  1. Fitness smart device has good market prospects. People tends to frequently use device to record their activity, willing to pay more attention to their health issue.
  2. Averaged daily activity intensity for most people is not sufficient for general fitness. -Daily step and distance for most people is less than recommended daily step and distance -Most of recorded activity is sedentary mintues, which is negatively correlated with calories. Market advertising could focus on these issues, encouraging customers to pay more attention to their health, using smart decive to track their fitness.
